items.paragraph:
The Operator shall have a security management system (SeMS) that includes, as a minimum, th ollowing key elements:

	(i) Senior management and corporate commitment;

	(ii) Resource management;

	(iii) Threat assessment and risk management;

	(iv) Management of emergencies and incidents (resilience);

	(v) Quality control and quality assurance;

	(vi) Air Operator Security Program (AOSP).

The Operator shall have a corporate security policy that states the commitment of the organization t  culture that has security as a fundamental operational priority. Such policy shall be communicate hroughout the organization and commit the organization to:

	(i) The provision of resources necessary for the successful implementation of the policy;

	(ii) Compliance with applicable regulations and standards of the Operator;

	(iii) The promotion of security awareness and the establishment of a security culture;

	(iv) The establishment of security objectives and security performance standards;

	(v) Continual improvement of the SeMS;

	(vi) Periodic review of the policy to ensure continuing relevance to the organization.

The Operator shall have a formal Air Operator Security Program (AOSP) that includes:

	(i) The requirements of the civil aviation security program of the State of the Operator
(hereinafter, the State);

	(ii) Supplementary Station Procedures (SSP) that meet the requirements of other states wher perations are conducted;

	(iii) The security standards of the Operator.

The Operator shall ensure the SeMS defines the authorities and responsibilities of managemen ersonnel within the SeMS and provides a general description of security responsibilities fo ategories of non-management personnel within the SeMS as documented in the AOSP. The SeM hall specify:

	(i) The levels of management with the authority to make decisions that affect operationa ecurity;

	(ii) Responsibilities for ensuring security functions are performed and procedures ar mplemented in accordance with applicable regulations and standards of the Operator;

	(iii) Lines of accountability throughout the SeMS, including direct accountability for security o he part of senior management;

	(iv) Responsibilities of members of management, irrespective of other functions, as well as o on-management personnel, with respect to security performance of the SeMS.

If permitted by the State, the Operator shall ensure a process has been established that require perational security personnel in the organization of the Operator and, if applicable, service provider elected by the Operator to conduct operational security functions, to be subjected to pre-
employment and recurring background checks in accordance with requirements of applicabl viation security authorities. The requirement for a background check shall be applicable t ersonnel who:

	(i) Engage in the implementation of security controls;

	(ii) Have unescorted access to the security restricted area of an airport;

	(iii) Have unescorted access to other security areas and searched aircraft;

	(iv) Have access to sensitive aviation security information.

The Operator shall have a system for the management and control of documentation and/or dat sed directly in the conduct or support of operations, and in the implementation of the AOSP and it ssociated SSPs to ensure that they:

	(i) Meet all required elements specified in Table 1.1 ;

	(ii) Contain legible and accurate information;

	(iii) Presented in a format appropriate for use in operations.

The Operator shall have a system for the management and control of operational security records t nsure the content and retention of such records is in accordance with requirements of the aviatio ecurity authority of the State, as applicable, and to ensure security records are subjected t tandardized processes for:

	(i) Identification;

	(ii) Legibility;

	(iii) Maintenance;

	(iv) Retrieval;

	(v) Protection, integrity and security;

	(vi) Disposal, deletion (electronic records) and archiving, including retention and storage a andated by the State.

The Operator shall have a security review committee for the purpose of ensuring:

	(i) Senior management oversight of security in operations;

	(ii) Continual improvement of the SeMS;

	(iii) Security threats are being identified and controlled;

	(iv) The promotion of security awareness.

The Operator shall have a quality assurance program that provides for the auditing and evaluation o he management system and operational security functions at a determined frequency following  egularly performed risk assessment to ensure the organization is:

	(i) Complying with the AOSP and its associated SSPs and other applicable regulations an tandards;

	(ii) Satisfying stated operational needs;

	(iii) Identifying areas requiring improvement;

	(iv) Identifying threats to operations;

	(v) Assessing the effectiveness of security risk management and controls.

The Operator shall have a process for addressing findings resulting from audits of operationa ecurity functions that ensures:

	(i) Identification of root cause(s);

	(ii) Development of corrective action, as appropriate, to address findings;

	(iii) Implementation of corrective action in appropriate operational security area(s);

	(iv) Evaluation of corrective action to determine effectiveness.

The Operator shall have an audit planning process and sufficient resources, including auditors a pecified in ORG 2.1.8 , to ensure audits are:

	(i) Scheduled in accordance with a security risk assessment at intervals to meet regulatory an anagement system requirements;

	(ii) Conducted within the scheduled interval (subject to a change in risk).

If required and/or authorized by the aviation security authority, the Operator shall have a process t erform or participate in periodic operational security exercises in order to:

	(i) Evaluate the effectiveness of procedures designed for response to security incidents;

	(ii) Practice implementation of security procedures by applicable personnel.

If the Operator has external service providers conduct outsourced aviation security functions, th perator should ensure a service provider selection process is in place that ensures:

	(i) Security-relevant selection criteria are established;

	(ii) Service providers are evaluated against these criteria prior to selection.

The Operator shall have an operational security reporting system that is implemented throughout th rganization in a manner that:

	(i) Encourages and facilitates personnel to report security incidents and security occurrence ertaining to the Operator;

	(ii) Ensures mandatory reporting in accordance with applicable regulations;

	(iii) Includes analysis and management action as necessary to address security issue dentified through the reporting system.

The Operator shall have a process to ensure security information, security incidents, securit ccurrences and acts of unlawful interference that have been reported by personnel in accordanc ith SEC 1.12.1 or are derived from states or other relevant sources are reviewed by operational an ecurity management to ensure:

	(i) Root cause is identified;

	(ii) A security risk assessment is conducted;

	(iii) Corrective action is determined;

	(iv) When applicable, corrective action is implemented and monitored to ensure effectiveness i reventing future incidents or occurrences.

If the Operator has operational security functions conducted by external service providers selecte y the Operator (outsourcing), the Operator shall have a process to ensure such external servic roviders have a security training program that:

	(i) Is acceptable to the Operator;

	(ii) Consists of initial, recurrent and, where applicable, requalification training;

	(iii) Includes, as appropriate, theoretical and practical training;

	(iv) Includes an assessment of competencies;

	(v) Ensures personnel have a common understanding of security awareness and reporting.

If the Operator manages a security screening system, the Operator shall ensure personnel wh anage or operate the screening system:

	(i) Are approved and/or certified in accordance with requirements of the applicable aviatio ecurity authority;

	(ii) Complete initial and recurrent training that includes training in the identification o xplosives, weapons or other dangerous items or devices.

The security training program of the Operator shall include a process for reviewing and updating o evising security training courses to ensure:

	(i) Continual improvement of curriculum, including content and applicability to the operationa nvironment;

	(ii) Incorporation of regulatory amendments or operational changes.

If the Operator has exclusive control over airport airside areas and/or security restricted areas, th perator shall ensure an identification verification system is in place that prevents personnel an ehicles from unauthorized access. Such identification system shall include:

	(i) Designated checkpoints where identification is verified before access is permitted;

	(ii) A requirement for authorized personnel to prominently display an identification badge.

If the carriage of weapons in hold baggage on board an aircraft for a passenger flight is approved b he Operator, the Operator shall have procedures for the carriage of such weapons to ensure:

	(i) If the weapon is a firearm or capable of discharging a projectile, the passenger or a uthorized and duly qualified person has declared the weapon to be not loaded;

	(ii) The weapon is stowed in a place that is inaccessible to any unauthorized person durin light;

	(iii) The carriage of a weapon is legally permitted by all state(s) involved, including the State an tate(s) of flight departure, transit and arrival.

If the Operator conducts passenger flights, the Operator shall have a process to ensure originatin assengers and their cabin baggage are subjected to screening prior to boarding a passenge ircraft for;

	(i) An international flight;

	(ii) As required by the applicable aviation security authority, a domestic flight.

If the Operator conducts passenger flights, the Operator shall have a process to ensure passenger nd their cabin baggage, which have already been subjected to screening, are:

	(i) Protected from unauthorized interference from the point of screening until they board  assenger aircraft;

	(ii) Subjected to re-screening if the potential for unauthorized interference has been determine o exist.

If the Operator conducts international passenger flights, the Operator shall have a process to ensur riginating hold baggage, including courier baggage, is:

	(i) Subjected to screening capable of detecting explosives and explosive devices prior to bein oaded into an aircraft for an international passenger flight;

	(ii) Protected from unauthorized interference from the moment of acceptance until loaded o oard the aircraft.

If the Operator conducts domestic passenger flights, the Operator should have a process to ensur riginating hold baggage is:

	(i) Subjected to screening capable of detecting explosives and explosive devices prior to bein oaded into an aircraft for a domestic passenger flight;

	(ii) Protected from unauthorized interference from the moment of acceptance until they ar oaded on board the aircraft.

If the Operator conducts international passenger flights, the Operator shall have a process to ensur rocedures are in place to prevent items of hold baggage from being transported on such flight nless such items have been:

	(i) Individually identified as either accompanied or unaccompanied baggage;

	(ii) Subjected to appropriate security controls based on risk assessment.

The Operator shall have processes for maintaining a constant review of the level and nature o ecurity and cybersecurity threats to civil aviation, and for identifying direct or potential threat gainst the Operator and/or its aircraft operations. For threats that have been identified, suc rocesses shall include:

	(i) An assessment of associated risks and vulnerabilities;

	(ii) Development of appropriate response measures.

The Operator shall have a process to ensure the implementation of appropriate security measures i esponse to:

	(i) Security threats directed against the Operator;

	(ii) Threat levels issued by applicable aviation security authorities.

The Operator shall have a process to ensure an investigation is conducted for any of the following:

	(i) Threats or acts of unlawful interference;

	(ii) Failure of implementation of security controls under the responsibility of the Operator;

	(iii) Security incidents, security occurrences or security threats.
